name: World of Coca-Cola
text: Memorabilia, films & exhibits (some interactive) about soft drink that debuted in Atlanta in 1886.

name: Georgia Aquarium
text: One of world's largest aquariums, with permanent exhibits, interactive galleries & animals galore.

name: Fox Theatre
text: Restored opulent theater built in 1920s with 3,600-pipe organ hosts ballet, movies & other events.

name: Atlanta Botanical Garden
text: 30-acre garden with a conservatory & fountains playing host to concerts, cocktail parties & more.

name: Six Flags Over Georgia
text: Sprawling amusement park featuring high-speed roller coasters & water attractions, plus kids' rides.

name: High Museum of Art
text: Museum known for its diverse art collection & modern architecture by Richard Meier & Renzo Piano.

name: Atlanta History Center
text: Center includes exhibits on the antebellum South & an 1845-era farm with a blacksmith & smokehouse.

name: Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historical Park
text: National Park encompassing King's birth home, Ebenezer Baptist Church & his final resting place.

name: The King Center
text: Nonprofit center exhibiting MLK related photos & artifacts, plus rooms on Gandhi & Rosa Parks.

name: LEGO® Discovery Center Atlanta
text: Family entertainment center featuring LEGO® toy displays, rides & 4D films, plus a gift shop.

name: SkyView Atlanta
text: 20-story Ferris wheel in Centennial Park providing scenic views from climate-controlled gondolas.

name: Woodruff Arts Center
text: Cultural hub home to the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, the Alliance Theater & the High Museum of Art.

name: Center For Puppetry Arts
text: Long-standing puppetry museum with a variety of exhibits, performances, workshops & classes.

name: Rhodes Hall
text: Turn-of-the-century residence known as The Castle on Peachtree that's now a museum & event space.

name: Jimmy Carter Presidential Library and Museum
text: Housing documents of the 39th president, this museum also features a replica of the Oval Office.

name: Children's Museum of Atlanta
text: Recommended for kids age 2-8, this hands-on museum features an indoor playground, sand table & more.

name: Underground Atlanta
text: This historic area is now a shopping & entertainment center with eateries, events & tours.

name: Hindu Temple of Atlanta
text: Traditional Hindu place of worship with 2 temples featuring ornate carvings of deities.

name: Callanwolde Fine Arts Center
text: Community arts center in a mansion, with exhibits, concerts & workshops, plus outreach programs.

name: Oakland Cemetery
text: This historic 1850s cemetery is the burial site of Margaret Mitchell & other notable locals.

name: Michael C. Carlos Museum
text: Museum of ancient art featuring Greek & Roman collections & an Egyptian exhibit including mummies.

name: Candler Park
text: Neighborhood park features an elaborate wooden playground, a pavilion, a multi-use field & a pool.

name: Lakewood Amphitheatre
text: Major concert & festival venue with both reserved seating & a sloping lawn.

name: MODA (Museum of Design Atlanta)
text: Small gallery space featuring rotating exhibitions that explore the impact of design on art & life.

name: Swan House at Atlanta History Center
text: Restored Philip T. Shutze designed 1928 neoclassical mansion & gardens built for rich cotton heirs.

name: Central Park
text: 17-acre recreational facility includes paths, athletic fields, a playground & a recreational center.

name: Catholic Shrine of the Immaculate Conception
Basilica of the Sacred Heart of Jesus
Cabbagetown Park
text: Pint-sized neighborhood park featuring a children's playground, stone sculptures & more.

name: Historic Fourth Ward Park
text: A 17-acre park with a splash fountain, skate park & amphitheater, adjacent to the Atlanta Beltline.

name: Hammonds House Museum
text: Quaint, Victorian house showcasing diverse works by artists of African decent, plus lectures & more.

name: Blackburn Park
text: In addition to multi-use fields & trails, this park houses a tennis center with lighted hard courts.

name: Piedmont Dog Park
text: Fenced off-leash dog park on 3 acres, with small- & large-breed areas, shade, water & benches.

name: Frankie Allen Park
text: Public site with baseball diamonds, tennis courts, a picnic meadow & a small historic graveyard.

name: Delta Flight Museum
text: Kid-friendly museum tracing the history of Delta Airlines with hands-on exhibits & vintage aircraft.

name: Grant Park
text: Sprawling green space & recreational area is the heart of one of Atlanta's oldest neighborhoods.

name: Reynolds Nature Preserve
text: Vast natural wildlife & land conservation area combining rolling hills, forests & wetlands.

name: Apex Museum
text: African-American museum chronicling Auburn's history through exhibits, replicas & workshops.

name: Murphey Candler Park
text: 135-acre park offering walking trails around a lake, a swimming pool, sports fields & picnic areas.

name: Ebenezer Baptist Church
text: Historic, preserved church where both Martin Luther King, Jr. and his father were preachers.

name: Millennium Gate Museum - History Art Museum Atlanta, Georgia | Classical Architecture
text: 12,000-square-foot interactive museum shaped like an arch dedicated to state history, art & culture.

name: Robert C. Williams Museum of Papermaking
text: A history of paper with more 2,000 books, papers, tools, machines & manuscripts.

name: Chattahoochee NRA--Powers Island Unit
text: Park on the Chattahoochee River Water Trail with areas for hiking, biking, canoeing & bird-watching.

name: Museum of Contemporary Art of Georgia
text: Museum founded in 2000 to showcase significant contemporary works by Georgian visual artists.

name: Henderson Park
text: A public park with a waterfall, soccer fields, tennis courts, trails & a community garden.

name: Emma Millican Park
text: This scenic neighborhood park features multiple play structures, shade trees, paths & picnic areas.

name: Rosa L. Burney Park
text: Urban park with lawns, a playground, tennis courts, softball fields & an indoor recreation center.

name: Hapeville Depot Museum and Visitor Center
DeKalb History Center Museum
text: Local-history artifacts & unique exhibits inside a stately historic courthouse building.

name: Walton Spring Park
text: This small downtown plaza features shade trees & a circular seating area around an obelisk.
